{"id": "duc04-testb-23:8#25", "contents": "The biggest problem facing American companies is the inability of many nations and companies in Asia and Latin America to borrow money to make ordinary purchases, resulting in a freeze of economic activity. This is hurting various industries, including Midwest farmers and East Coast fishermen. A surprising element of the report is that more than a third of August's deficit was with China, despite the country's continued growth. Exports to China have slowed dramatically, and imports of Chinese-made goods have exploded, increasing the monthly deficit with Beijing to $5.9 billion. This has significant implications for President Clinton's efforts to open China's markets further in return for entry into the World Trade Organization."}
